{"title_page": "Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle''' is a 16th and 17th century [[castle]] in the ''[[Communes of France|commune]]'' of [[Muret]] in the [[Haute-Garonne]] ''[[Departments of France|d\u00e9partement]]'' of France.<ref name=MinCult>Ministry of Culture: [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&REQ=((PA00094404):REF) Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nThe castle is noted for its ancient chimneys and for [[murals]] painted on the third floor.\n\nIt was built by Guillaume de Rudelle, the son of Jean de Rudelle, a counsellor to the king. In 1783, Jean-Marie-Joseph Ingres, the father of the famous artist [[Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres]], stayed there and painted several ceilings. At the [[French Revolution]], the property was taken as a national asset and sold at auction.<ref name=MinCult/>\n\nThe building today has a reactangular plan within square towers at each corner.  On the south, a square tower projects slightly. On the top floor, immediately below the roof, is a series of arcades on the north and south fa\u00e7ades. Mullioned windows decorate the fa\u00e7ade. The upper floors are reached by a wooden spiral staircase.<ref name=MinCult/>\n\nPrivately owned, it has been listed since 1979 as a ''[[monument historique]]'' by the [[French Ministry of Culture]].<ref name=MinCult/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of castles in France]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&REQ=((PA00094404):REF) Ministry of Culture listing for Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Coord|43|27|7|N|1|18|38|E|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rudelle, Chateau De}}\n[[Category:Castles in Haute-Garonne]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Haute-Garonne]]\n\n\n{{France-castle-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\nThe '''Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle''' is a 16th and 17th century [[castle]] in the ''[[Communes of France|commune]]'' of [[Muret]] in the [[Haute-Garonne]] ''[[Departments of France|d\u00e9partement]]'' of France.<ref name=MinCult>Ministry of Culture: [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&REQ=((PA00094404):REF) Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nThe castle is noted for its ancient chimneys and for [[murals]] painted on the third floor. \n\nIt was built by Guillaume de Rudelle, the son of Jean de Rudelle, a counsellor to the king. In 1783, Jean-Marie-Joseph Ingres, the father of the famous artist [[Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres]], stayed there and painted several ceilings. At the [[French Revolution]], the property was taken as a national asset and sold at auction.<ref name=MinCult/>\n\nThe building today has a reactangular plan within square towers at each corner.  On the south, a square tower projects slightly. On the top floor, immediately below the roof, is a series of arcades on the north and south fa\u00e7ades. Mullioned windows decorate the fa\u00e7ade. The upper floors are reached by a wooden spiral staircase.<ref name=MinCult/>\n\nPrivately owned, it has been listed since 1979 as a ''[[monument historique]]'' by the [[French Ministry of Culture]].<ref name=MinCult/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of castles in France]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&REQ=((PA00094404):REF) Ministry of Culture listing for Ch\u00e2teau de Rudelle] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n\n{{Coord|43|27|7|N|1|18|38|E|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rudelle, Chateau De}}\n[[Category:Castles in Haute-Garonne]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Haute-Garonne]]\n\n\n{{France-castle-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch%C3%A2teau_de_Rudel